<HEADLINE>
<P>
DEALING WITH OIL TANKER ACCIDENTS IN COASTAL WATERS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Larry Stammer's article on the plight of the Gulf of Mexico really hit home 
with me (front page, June 15). I grew up in Rockport, Texas, 30 miles north of 
Corpus Christi and until this past month, I had not seen the gulf coast for 20 
years. 
</P>
<P>
When a returned to the gulf, I knew there would be changes along the vast 
virgin stretches of sandy beach where my friends and I had cruised. What I 
wasn't prepared to see was a coastal garbage dump. 
</P>
<P>
Besides the flotsam and bird carcasses, what I also found incredible was the 
people in the area claiming that the pollution was coming from Mexico. Of all 
the hundreds of washed up plastics and glass bottles, I never tripped over one 
that had Hecho en Mexico written on it. What I did notice were dozens of 
offshore drilling projects along the gulf horizon that didn't exist 20 years 
ago. 
</P>
<P>
Where does the debris on our beaches come from? The trash cans remain empty 
while most of the garbage lay washed up onshore. The offenders are the 
companies that are involved in the exploration and transport of oil found in 
these offshore drilling projects. Isn't it time that our state and federal 
politicians take a tougher stance on the regulatory practices of offshore 
drilling as well as stronger enforcement of laws that tolerate no leakage of 
oil from these projects? 
</P>
<P>
Thanks to Stammer's article, I am no longer apathetic about the 
de-gentrification of our shorelines. I am ready to join the protest. Everyone 
agrees that it's time to clean up the crime in our streets. How about cleaning 
up the crime in our oceans? 
</P>
<P>
JAY DAYS 
</P>
<P>
Los Angeles 
</P>
</TEXT>
