<HEADLINE>
<P>
METRO DIGEST / LOCAL NEWS IN BRIEF: MEXICAN FRUIT FLY FIND PROMPTS SETTING OF 
TRAPS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The discovery of a Mexican fruit fly this week in a trap in South Los Angeles 
has prompted agriculture officials to set scores of new traps to determine if 
there is an infestation in the area or if the fly is a so-called "lone 
hitchhiker." 
</P>
<P>
The unmated female fly was found in a trap that had been set in a lemon tree in 
a residence not far from the city's border with Vernon, said a spokesman for 
the state Department of Food and Agriculture. 
</P>
<P>
As a result, workers will set 80 additional traps in the square mile around the 
spot, 40 traps in the square mile surrounding that and 20, 10 and five traps in 
the successive square-mile zones. 
</P>
<P>
Some of the fruit that attracts the Mexican fruit fly is the same that appeals 
to the Mediterranean fruit fly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
